{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/14942.Mrs_Dalloway", "title": "Mrs. Dalloway", "titleComplete": "Mrs. Dalloway", "description": "Heralded as Virginia Woolf's greatest novel, this is a vivid portrait of a single day in a woman's life. When we meet her, Mrs. Clarissa Dalloway is preoccupied with the last-minute details of party preparation while in her mind she is something much more than a perfect society hostess. As she readies her house, she is flooded with remembrances of faraway times. And, met with the realities of the present, Clarissa reexamines the choices that brought her there, hesitantly looking ahead to the unfamiliar work of growing old.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1646148221i/14942.jpg", "genres": ["School", "Classics", "Feminism", "English Literature", "Fiction", "Novels", "Literature", "20th Century", "British Literature", "Literary Fiction"], "asin": "0151009988", "isbn": "0151009988", "isbn13": "9780151009985", "publisher": "Houghton Mifflin Harcourt", "author": ["Virginia Woolf", "Maureen Howard"], "publishDate": 1035792000000, "characters": ["Elizabeth Dalloway", "Doris Kilman", "Richard Dalloway", "Sir William Bradshaw", "Clarissa Dalloway", "Peter Walsh", "Hugh Whitbread", "Septimus Warren Smith", "Sally Seton", "Lucrezia Smith"], "places": ["London, England", "United Kingdom", "England"], "ratingHistogram": [10486, 25135, 70420, 98900, 90553], "ratingsCount": 295494, "reviewsCount": 17148, "numPages": 194, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16902.Walden", "title": "Walden", "titleComplete": "Walden", "description": "Originally published in 1854, Walden; or, Life in the Woods, is a vivid account of the time that Henry D. Thoreau lived alone in a secluded cabin at Walden Pond. It is one of the most influential and compelling books in American literature. This new paperback edition-introduced by noted American writer John Updike-celebrates the 150th anniversary of this classic work. Much of Walden's material is derived from Thoreau's journals and contains such engaging pieces as \"Reading\" and \"The Pond in the Winter\" Other famous sections involve Thoreau's visits with a Canadian woodcutter and with an Irish family, a trip to Concord, and a description of his bean field. This is the complete and authoritative text of Walden-as close to Thoreau's original intention as all available evidence allows. For the student and for the general reader, this is the ideal presentation of Thoreau's great document of social criticism and dissent.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1630470982i/16902.jpg", "genres": ["Classics", "Biography", "Memoir", "Nature", "Philosophy", "Essays", "American", "Environment", "Literature", "Nonfiction"], "publisher": "Princeton University Press", "author": ["Henry David Thoreau", "Bill McKibben"], "publishDate": 1082271600000, "characters": ["Henry David Thoreau"], "places": ["Concord, Massachusetts", "The United States of America"], "ratingHistogram": [8146, 16287, 43067, 59996, 58510], "ratingsCount": 186006, "reviewsCount": 7469, "numPages": 352, "language": "English"}
